summary:
The Security Council,
Recalling previous resolutions and statements on the Central African Republic (CAR),
Welcoming efforts to reform the security sector, including deployment of CAR defence and security forces,
Encouraging implementation of the National Defence Plan, Force Employment Concept, and National Security Policy,
Acknowledging the need for training and equipping defence and security forces to protect citizens and promote human rights,
Expressing concern that some signatories to the Peace Agreement disregard their commitments,
Urging all signatories to implement the Peace Agreement in good faith,
Taking note of the CAR authorities' request to lift the arms embargo,
Recalling the Committee's approval of exemption requests submitted by the CAR authorities,
Reiterating readiness to review arms embargo measures, through suspension or lifting, based on progress on key benchmarks,
Welcoming progress on the operationalization of the Commission nationale de lutte contre la prolifération des armes légères,
Adoption of the Law on the General Regime for Conventional Weapons, and establishment of a Committee for Coordination of Mechanisms,
Encouraging continued efforts to reform security forces, implement Disarmament, Demobilisation, Reintegration and Repatriation (DDRR),
Welcoming efforts by the Panel of Experts to investigate violations of the arms embargo,
Recalling that deliveries of weapons and military equipment should only be used for support of or use in the CAR process of security sector reform.
The Security Council:

Noting the Secretary-General's letter and the Central African Republic (CAR) authorities' reports, and the final report of the Panel of Experts on the CAR,

Determining that the situation in the CAR continues to threaten international peace and security,

Acting under Chapter VII of the UN Charter,

1. Imposes an arms embargo on the CAR until 31 July 2022, with exceptions for:
	* Supplies for MINUSCA, EU training missions, French forces, and other forces providing training and assistance (a);
	* Non-lethal equipment and assistance for CAR security forces for security sector reform (SSR) (b);
	* Supplies for Chadian or Sudanese forces for international patrols (c);
	* Non-lethal military equipment for humanitarian or protective use (d);
	* Protective clothing for UN personnel, media, and humanitarian workers (e);
	* Supplies for international-led patrols and armed wildlife rangers (f);
	* Supplies of weapons with a calibre of 14.5 mm or less, and related assistance, for CAR security forces for SSR (g);
	* Supplies of arms and lethal equipment, and related assistance, for CAR security forces for SSR, approved in advance by the Committee (h);
	* Other sales or supply of arms and materiel, or provision of assistance or personnel, approved in advance by the Committee (i);

2. Requires notifications for supplies and assistance permitted under paragraphs 1 (d), (f), and (g) to be made at least 20 days in advance;

3. Renews measures and provisions set out in resolutions 2488 (2019) and 2399 (2018) until 31 July 2022;

4. Renews measures and provisions set out in paragraphs 9, 14, and 16 to 19 of resolution 2399 (2018) until 31 July 2022;

5. Reaffirms measures described in paragraphs 9 and 16 of resolution 2399 (2018) apply to individuals and entities designated by the Committee;

6. Extends the mandate of the Panel of Experts until 31 August 2022 and requests the Secretary-General to re-establish the Panel;

7. Requests the Panel of Experts to provide a midterm report by 31 January 2022, a final report by 30 June 2022, and progress updates.
The Security Council:

8. Expresses concern about illicit transnational trafficking networks funding and supplying armed groups in the CAR, and requests the Panel to analyze such networks in cooperation with other Panels or Groups of Experts;

9. Urges all parties, Member States, and organizations to ensure cooperation with the Panel of Experts and the safety of its members;

10. Urges Member States and UN bodies to ensure unhindered access to persons, documents, and sites for the Panel to execute its mandate;

11. Reaffirms Committee provisions and reporting and review provisions as set out in resolutions 2399 (2018) and 2536 (2020);

12. Requests the CAR authorities to report by 15 June 2022 on progress regarding SSR, DDRR process, and management of weapons and ammunition;

13. Requests the Secretary-General to conduct an assessment by 15 June 2022 on progress achieved by the CAR authorities on key benchmarks;

14. Affirms it will keep the situation in the CAR under review and be prepared to review measures in light of the security situation, progress achieved, and compliance;

15. Decides to remain actively seized of the matter.
